data.Plant Description:
The best known of all, a perennial herb with cooling and refreshing power. Pick the mint leaves  for all aspects of cookery while they are young and fresh. You can also dry leaves and preserve it.
The roots have tendency to spread far and wide. So keep a check to prevent it from taking over the entire garden.
data.Usage and Benefits:
Medicinal Use/Health Benefits- 
- It treats Indigestion and ease upset stomach.
- Chewing few mint leaves gives oral freshness and prevents from bad breath.
- It can cure common cold and headaches as it has anti-inflammatory and anti-bacterial properties.

Culinary Use-
- The leaves are used as flavouring agent in beverages.
- Chopped mint leaves are used in garnishing various dishes.
- Sprinkle dried mint leaves in curries, soups, vegetables and meat.
- Add up pudina chutney in your plate and savour the benefits like appeite enhancement.
data.Planting/Harvesting Tips: Sow mint seeds indoor (8-10 weeks before frost) in spring. Plant them in large sized pot with 12 inches of space in between.

data.Plant Description: Coriander is a popular annual herb which adds up distinct flavour in almost every cuisine. The coriander leaves are bright green, has cut and varies in shape. The leaves imparts flavour and is a famous garnish in dishes. Flowers are small and white. Seeds which are used as a spice are used entire or grinded.
data.Usage and Benefits:
Medicinal Use/Health Benefits-
- It is good source of dietry fibre, iron, manganese and magnesium.
- Promotes bowel movement and hence, good for digestive system.
- It cures mouth ulcer and maintains oral hygeine.

Culinary Use-
- Stem, seed and leaves,  all three parts find place in kitchen.
- Leaves are used in seasoning and garnishing of dishes.
- Dried seeds are used as a spice in various dish.
data.Planting/Harvesting Tips:
Soak the seeds in water for 12 hours.
Sow the split seeds at a spacing of 2 inches.
The seeds will germinate in about 8-15 days.
The more you harvest coriander leaves, the more flowering gets delayed.

data.Plant Description: An aromatic perennial plant which can serve as herb as well as spice. Harvest the young leaves and collect the seed once it ripens. A multipurpose plant with leaves and seeds used in cuisines, bulb used as vegetable and is of ornamental use as well.

Culinary Use-
- It is low calorie superfood packed with Vitamin C, Calcium, Iron, Magnesium and Potassium.
- Bulb and leaves of fennel plant are used as a vegetable.
- Fennel seeds are used in pickles, soup, sauces, desserts and fish dishes.

data.Plant Description:

data.Plant Description: Sweet basil (Ocimum basilicium) is the basic species amongst several types of basil. The green variety of basil is the most commonly grown. It is particularly good in association with tomatoes, salads and in wide range of Mediterraean dishes.

data.Plant Description: Aloe vera is one of the most promising medicinal herb which is evergreen, perennial and belong to succulent plant species. It is grown for medicinal and ornamental purpose. data.Plant Description: Parsley can be grown as an annual herb in India. It has two forms- Curly-leaved parsley used as garnish and Flat-leaved parsley provide flavours in variety of dishes. data.Plant Description: Fenugreek or Kasturi methi is an annual herb. The leaves are used as herb and vegetable. The seeds are one of the famous spice used in Indian culinary.

data.Plant Name: Murraya koenigii/Curry Plant/ Sweet neem leaves/Kadi-patta

data.Plant Description: Dill is an annual herb with feathery leaves, similar to those of fennel and yellow flowers. The leaves and seeds are used as a herb or spice for flavouring food. Both of them are mainly used for fish dishes and salads.

data.Planting/Harvesting Tips: It is advisable to avoid planting dill near fennel  if you are planning to use the seeds of either plant, because the two herbs can cross-pollinate easily.

data.Plant Description:
